# lib/p9.ad
#
# #458 F10-6 — Plan 9 `Dir` record as first-class universal directory
# enumeration shape. The previous "directory read = NAME\n stream"
# fixed `p9_listdir`'s ABI but blocked `ls -l`, `stat`, and Plan 9's
# stream-of-Dir-records idiom from ever landing without a re-stat()
# per leaf. This file adds the wire format + an encoder/decoder pair
# (callable from both kernel-side directory backings and userspace
# parsers) + `p9_diread(fd)` that reads exactly ONE record from a fd
# whose backing was opened in Dir-record mode.
#
# DIR WIRE FORMAT (little-endian, length-prefixed)
# ================================================
# Each Dir record on the wire is:
#
#   off  size  field
#     0    2   reclen          total bytes of this record INCLUDING
#                              this length prefix; reader advances
#                              `off += reclen` to the next record.
#     2    1   qid_type        Plan 9 QTDIR / QTFILE / QTAUTH / ...
#     3    4   qid_version
#     7    8   qid_path        u64; unique-per-fileserver inode-shape
#    15    4   mode            Plan 9 perm bits (DMDIR | 0755 ...)
#    19    4   atime           u32 seconds since unix epoch
#    23    4   mtime           u32 seconds since unix epoch
#    27    8   length          u64 file length in bytes
#    35    2   name_len; name_len bytes of `name` (no NUL)
#    37+L  2   uid_len;  uid_len  bytes of `uid`  (no NUL)
#    ...   2   gid_len;  gid_len  bytes of `gid`  (no NUL)
#    ...   2   muid_len; muid_len bytes of `muid` (no NUL)
#
# Strings are NOT NUL-terminated on the wire — every string carries
# its own u16 length prefix immediately before its bytes. The fixed
# header (offsets 0..34) is 35 bytes; adding the four length prefixes
# (8 bytes) gives a 43-byte minimum record for an entry with empty
# uid/gid/muid and empty name. The `reclen` at offset 0 is the
# self-describing skip count, so a reader that doesn't know a field
# can still hop to the next record.
#
# This is a deliberately SMALLER shape than Plan 9 9P2000's stat wire
# format (which carries `type`/`dev`/`qid`/... and a redundant size
# prefix). Hamnix's namespace has no per-mount `type`/`dev` doublet —
# the file-server letter (#c, #s, #p, ...) is implicit in the
# directory being read — so those fields are omitted. The encoder
# refuses to overflow a caller-supplied buffer; a record that would
# not fit is reported as "truncated" via a 0 return and the caller
# stops emission.
#
# PER-CHAN OPT-IN
# ===============
# The kernel-side directory backings keep emitting the legacy
# "NAME\n" stream by default. A caller opts into the Dir wire format
# by opening through `p9_listdir_records` (SYS_LISTDIR_RECORDS, 287)
# which routes through the kernel's `devsrv_list_dir` (#s) emitter.
# Other devs (#p / on-disk / #c) keep their legacy line shape until a
# subsequent migration; the new syscall returns -ENOSYS for those
# paths so `p9_listdir` callers see no behaviour change.
#
# Original F6 header continues below.
#
# #450 F6 — Plan 9-shape userland helpers for what used to be drift
# syscalls (SYS_SPAWN / SYS_LISTDIR / SYS_KILL). The kernel side of
# Phase G retires those three syscall arms (numbers stay reserved per
# the F2 pattern); user code now uses the Plan-9-shape file + rfork
# primitives directly. This library is the thin glue.
#
# The "200-line magic SYS_SPAWN inheritance block" in
# arch/x86/kernel/syscall.ad goes away — the inheritance story is
# expressed where it should be: in userland, via rfork's flag set + an
# explicit dup2 + the existing sys_fdbind binding API. No kernel-side
# spawn() exists. Every fork+exec happens in userland.
#
# WHAT THIS PROVIDES
# ==================
#
#   spawn(path, argv, sin, sout, envp) -> int32
#       Plan-9 rfork+exec replacement for the retired SYS_SPAWN.
#       The flags are RFPROC | RFFDG | RFNAMEG so the child gets a
#       PRIVATE COW namespace (including a private /fd-name table) and
#       a PRIVATE fd table — same isolation guarantees the kernel arm
#       used to provide. The child handles stdin/stdout redirection via
#       sys_dup2 between rfork and exec for the legacy integer-fd case
#       (sin/sout in [0, 16)); for the SPAWN_STDIO_NS sentinel (-2) the
#       child runs untouched — the parent rebinds the child's /fd/N via
#       sys_fdbind(pid, ...) BEFORE yielding to it (cooperative
#       scheduler keeps the child STATE_READY across the spawn return).
#
#       Return: child pid in parent (>0), -1 on error (rfork failed),
#       127 in the child on exec failure (sys_exit(127), matches the
#       legacy "command not found" convention).
#
#   p9_note(pid, msg) -> int32
#       Plan-9 note (signal) replacement for the retired SYS_KILL. Opens
#       /proc/<pid>/note for write, writes `msg` (NUL-terminated), closes.
#       Layer 2 maps Linux signal numbers to note strings (docs/native-api.md
#       "Notes"); native callers pass the string directly.
#       Return: 0 on success, -1 on error.
#
#   p9_listdir(path, buf, count) -> int64
#       Plan-9 directory-read replacement for the retired SYS_LISTDIR.
#       open(path, OREAD) + read(fd, buf, count) + close(fd). The
#       backing FS still renders directory contents as "NAME\n" lines
#       (DEV_DIR_FILE / _dirfile_read), so the format the syscall used
#       to return is preserved here exactly. Callers parse "NAME\n"
#       records the same way they did before. Migrating to native-api.md's
#       9P Dir-record stream is a separate kernel-side track (the
#       kernel's stat/fstat already build Dir records; the dir-read path
#       still emits NAME\n until that switchover lands).
#       Return: bytes written into `buf` on success (>= 0), -1 on error
#       (open failure or the path is not a directory).
#
# COMPILER QUIRKS HONOURED: single-file module, no nested helpers, no
# adjacent string-literal concatenation.

from lib.p9dir import (
    p9_dir_encode_into, p9d_get_u16, p9d_get_u32, p9d_get_u64,
    P9_DMDIR,
    P9_DIR_FIXED_HDR, P9_DIR_MIN_REC,
)
from lib.9p.9p import P9_QTDIR, P9_QTFILE

extern def sys_rfork(flags: int32) -> int32
extern def sys_execve_env(path: Ptr[char], argv: Ptr[uint64],
                          envp: Ptr[uint64]) -> int32
extern def sys_dup2(oldfd: int32, newfd: int32) -> int32
extern def sys_open(path: Ptr[char]) -> int32
extern def sys_open_write(path: Ptr[char]) -> int32
extern def sys_read(fd: int32, buf: Ptr[uint8], count: uint64) -> int64
extern def sys_write(fd: int32, buf: Ptr[uint8], count: uint64) -> int64
extern def sys_close(fd: int32) -> int32
extern def sys_exit(code: uint64)
# sys_fdbind — install a backing channel at /fd/<fdnum> in pid's Pgrp
# (pid 0 == the CALLING task's own Pgrp). Mirrors the do_fdbind syscall
# body. spawn_stdio_pipes() uses it CHILD-SIDE so stdio inheritance is
# atomic at spawn — see that function's SMP-race note.
extern def sys_fdbind(pid: int32, fdnum: int32, kind: int32,
                      slot: int32) -> int32


# rfork flag bits (mirror sys/src/9/port/sysproc.ad's RF* constants).
P9_RFPROC:   int32 = 0x001
P9_RFFDG:    int32 = 0x004
P9_RFNAMEG:  int32 = 0x008
P9_RFENVG:   int32 = 0x010
P9_RFNOWAIT: int32 = 0x100            # detach — parent never reaps the child


# Sentinels carried over from the retired SYS_SPAWN ABI so callers don't
# need to learn new constants. -2 means "spawn-in-namespace mode" (parent
# does sys_fdbind on the child); -1 means "inherit parent's fd". Anything
# in [0, 16) is a real parent fd to dup into the child's slot.
P9_SPAWN_STDIO_NS: int32 = -2
P9_SPAWN_STDIO_INHERIT: int32 = -1


# DEVFD backing kinds (mirror sys/src/9/port/devfd.ad). Used by
# spawn_stdio_pipes() to bind the child's /fd/0,1,2 to pipe ends.
P9_DEVFD_PIPE_R: int32 = 2       # bind the READ end of a pipe slot
P9_DEVFD_PIPE_W: int32 = 3       # bind the WRITE end of a pipe slot


# _p9_path_buf: scratch path renderer for /proc/<pid>/note. Single-file
# module scope so the buffer is BSS, matching the rest of the userland
# convention (no malloc).
_p9_path_buf: Array[64, uint8]


def _p9_render_u32(v: uint32, out: Ptr[uint8], cap: uint64) -> uint64:
    # Render `v` as decimal into `out`, NUL-terminated. Returns the
    # length without the NUL. Caller guarantees cap >= 12.
    if v == 0:
        out[0] = 48                              # '0'
        out[1] = 0
        return 1
    digits: Array[12, uint8]
    n: uint64 = 0
    vv: uint64 = cast[uint64](v)
    while vv != 0 and n < 12:
        digits[n] = cast[uint8](48 + (vv % 10))
        vv = vv / 10
        n = n + 1
    # Reverse into out.
    i: uint64 = 0
    while i < n and i + 1 < cap:
        out[i] = digits[n - 1 - i]
        i = i + 1
    out[i] = 0
    return i


def _p9_build_note_path(pid: int32) -> Ptr[char]:
    # Render "/proc/<pid>/note" into _p9_path_buf and return it as
    # Ptr[char]. NUL-terminated.
    p: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](&_p9_path_buf[0])
    # "/proc/" prefix.
    p[0] = 47                                    # '/'
    p[1] = 112                                   # 'p'
    p[2] = 114                                   # 'r'
    p[3] = 111                                   # 'o'
    p[4] = 99                                    # 'c'
    p[5] = 47                                    # '/'
    off: uint64 = 6
    nlen: uint64 = _p9_render_u32(cast[uint32](pid),
                                  cast[Ptr[uint8]](&_p9_path_buf[off]),
                                  64 - off)
    off = off + nlen
    # "/note" suffix.
    if off + 5 >= 64:
        # Shouldn't happen — a 32-bit pid renders to <= 10 digits, so
        # 6 + 10 + 5 = 21 bytes total — well under 64. Defensive only.
        return cast[Ptr[char]](&_p9_path_buf[0])
    p[off] = 47                                  # '/'
    p[off + 1] = 110                             # 'n'
    p[off + 2] = 111                             # 'o'
    p[off + 3] = 116                             # 't'
    p[off + 4] = 101                             # 'e'
    p[off + 5] = 0
    return cast[Ptr[char]](&_p9_path_buf[0])


def _p9_strlen(s: Ptr[uint8]) -> uint64:
    n: uint64 = 0
    while s[n] != 0:
        n = n + 1
    return n


# --- spawn() — rfork+exec, the SYS_SPAWN replacement ---------------

def _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(fdnum: int32, fdname: Ptr[char]):
    # SPAWN_STDIO_NS contract: the child's integer fd `fdnum` resolves
    # through the /fd/<N> name in its (already-cloned) Pgrp, so the
    # parent's sys_fdbind(child_pid, fdnum, ...) rebinds take effect on
    # the child's reads/writes. The OLD kernel SYS_SPAWN block did this
    # by installing FD_CHAN_MARK + DEV_DEVFD inline-chan ids directly
    # into the child's TaskStruct fd table. Userland can't write
    # TaskStruct, but it can achieve the SAME routing by opening the
    # /fd/<N> namespace name and dup2'ing the resulting fd onto fdnum:
    # vfs.namec rewrites the open into the same FD_CHAN_MARK+DEV_DEVFD
    # fd the kernel arm used to plant. Once dup2'd, integer-fd reads
    # /writes route through /fd/<N> — and any subsequent
    # sys_fdbind(child, N, ...) by the parent retargets that name.
    newfd: int32 = sys_open(fdname)
    if newfd < 0:
        return
    if newfd != fdnum:
        sys_dup2(newfd, fdnum)
        sys_close(newfd)


def _spawn_flags(path: Ptr[char], argv: Ptr[uint64],
                 sin: int32, sout: int32, envp: Ptr[uint64],
                 extra_flags: int32) -> int32:
    # Plan 9-shape spawn. RFPROC creates the child; RFFDG gives it a
    # PRIVATE fd-table copy; RFNAMEG gives it a PRIVATE COW Pgrp (which
    # carries a COW copy of the caller's mtab + /fd-name table). These
    # three flags reproduce the isolation the kernel's old SYS_SPAWN
    # block did for SPAWN_STDIO_NS, without any kernel-side magic — the
    # rfork primitive alone is enough. `extra_flags` lets a caller add
    # RFNOWAIT (detach) — see spawn_detached.
    flags: int32 = P9_RFPROC | P9_RFFDG | P9_RFNAMEG | extra_flags
    pid: int32 = sys_rfork(flags)
    if pid < 0:
        return -1
    if pid != 0:
        # Parent: child pid is returned. The parent typically calls
        # sys_fdbind(pid, ...) to wire pipe/redirect/dup at the child's
        # /fd/N names; the cooperative scheduler keeps the child
        # STATE_READY through this call so binds land before the child
        # ever runs.
        return pid
    # Child: handle the integer-fd contract before exec.
    #
    # SPAWN_STDIO_NS (-2): the parent will rebind the child's /fd/N
    # names via sys_fdbind, so the child must route its integer fd
    # 0/1/2 through the /fd-name table for those binds to take effect
    # on reads/writes. The OLD kernel arm planted FD_CHAN_MARK +
    # DEV_DEVFD inline-chan ids directly; we achieve the same routing
    # in userland by opening the /fd/<N> name and dup2'ing it onto
    # the integer slot. The parent's sys_fdbind on the cloned-COW
    # Pgrp's /fd-name table then steers what /fd/<N> resolves to.
    if sin == P9_SPAWN_STDIO_NS:
        _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(0, cast[Ptr[char]]("/fd/0"))
    if sout == P9_SPAWN_STDIO_NS:
        _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(1, cast[Ptr[char]]("/fd/1"))
        # fd 2 / stderr: the OLD SYS_SPAWN block also routed fd 2
        # through /fd/2. We do the same here so a child's writes to
        # stderr land in the right place after a 2>&1 / 2>file
        # parent-side rebind.
        _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(2, cast[Ptr[char]]("/fd/2"))
    # Legacy integer-fd cases: an explicit fd number in [0, 16) means
    # "dup2 the parent's fd N onto the child's fd 0 / 1". -1 means
    # "inherit the parent's fd N" which RFFDG already gave us.
    if sin >= 0 and sin < 16:
        sys_dup2(sin, 0)
    if sout >= 0 and sout < 16:
        sys_dup2(sout, 1)
    # exec. sys_execve_env doesn't return on success. On failure (bad
    # path, malformed ELF, ENOENT) we exit 127 to match the legacy
    # SYS_SPAWN "command not found" convention so callers can keep their
    # exit-code probes.
    sys_execve_env(path, argv, envp)
    sys_exit(127)
    return 127                                   # unreached


def spawn(path: Ptr[char], argv: Ptr[uint64],
          sin: int32, sout: int32, envp: Ptr[uint64]) -> int32:
    # Standard spawn: the child is a normal, WAITABLE child. The caller is
    # responsible for reaping it via wait4 (hamsh does this for foreground
    # commands). Do NOT use this for fire-and-forget launches from a
    # long-running service that never wait4s — use spawn_detached, or the
    # child leaks its whole address space as an un-reapable zombie.
    return _spawn_flags(path, argv, sin, sout, envp, 0)


def spawn_detached(path: Ptr[char], argv: Ptr[uint64],
                   sin: int32, sout: int32, envp: Ptr[uint64]) -> int32:
    # Fire-and-forget spawn: RFNOWAIT severs the parent link at creation, so
    # the child is published as a DETACHED zombie on exit and the kernel's
    # reap_orphan_zombies() (run at every fork) reclaims it — no wait4 needed.
    #
    # This is the CORRECT launcher for the DE's long-running service parents
    # (the scene panel, the file manager) that fire off apps/editors and never
    # wait4 them. With the plain spawn() those children stayed NON-detached
    # zombies with a still-live parent, which reap_orphan_zombies() leaves for
    # a wait4 that never comes — so each menu launch / hamedit re-open leaked a
    # full address space until fork() hit -EAGAIN (the "menu app-launch breaks"
    # / "editor won't re-open" DE bugs).
    return _spawn_flags(path, argv, sin, sout, envp, P9_RFNOWAIT)


# --- spawn_stdio_pipes() — ATOMIC-at-spawn pipe stdio inheritance ---
#
# THE SMP FIX (#136). The plain SPAWN_STDIO_NS contract is: parent
# spawns, then calls sys_fdbind(child_pid, 0/1/2, ...) to steer the
# child's /fd names. That relies on the child staying STATE_READY
# "until the parent yields" — true ONLY on a UP cooperative scheduler.
# Under -smp 2 a SECOND CPU runs the child (routes its integer stdio +
# execs) BEFORE the parent's post-spawn binds land, so the child's
# /fd/0,1,2 still resolve to the INHERITED console — `ssh host <cmd>`
# and interactive input never reach the shell.
#
# This variant closes the race by binding the child's OWN /fd/0,1,2 to
# the pipe ends CHILD-SIDE, in the child's private COW Pgrp, BEFORE
# execve — a straight-line sequence in the child's single thread, so it
# is complete on whichever CPU runs the child before hamsh's first
# instruction (and before hamsh's getty-flush kind-probe of /fd/0). No
# cross-CPU ordering is involved: the parent does NO post-spawn stdio
# bind at all.
#
#   pin_slot  : pipe slot whose READ end becomes the child's /fd/0
#               (its stdin). The parent holds the WRITE end.
#   pout_slot : pipe slot whose WRITE end becomes the child's /fd/1 AND
#               /fd/2 (stdout+stderr). The parent holds the READ end.
#
# Pipe slots are GLOBAL, address-independent handles, so the values the
# parent computed are valid in the child's COW-copied frame. The parent
# must have already bound its own end of each pipe (so pin has a live
# writer / pout a live reader before the child can read) — exactly the
# pre-spawn ordering _spawn_shell uses.
def spawn_stdio_pipes(path: Ptr[char], argv: Ptr[uint64],
                      pin_slot: int32, pout_slot: int32,
                      envp: Ptr[uint64]) -> int32:
    flags: int32 = P9_RFPROC | P9_RFFDG | P9_RFNAMEG
    pid: int32 = sys_rfork(flags)
    if pid < 0:
        return -1
    if pid != 0:
        # Parent: child pid. NO post-spawn sys_fdbind — the child wires
        # its own stdio below, so there is nothing left to race.
        return pid
    # Child: bind OUR OWN /fd/0,1,2 (pid 0 == self) to the pipe ends in
    # our private COW Pgrp, then route the integer fds through those
    # names, then exec. All straight-line, pre-exec, race-free.
    sys_fdbind(0, 0, P9_DEVFD_PIPE_R, pin_slot)
    sys_fdbind(0, 1, P9_DEVFD_PIPE_W, pout_slot)
    sys_fdbind(0, 2, P9_DEVFD_PIPE_W, pout_slot)
    _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(0, cast[Ptr[char]]("/fd/0"))
    _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(1, cast[Ptr[char]]("/fd/1"))
    _p9_route_stdio_through_fdname(2, cast[Ptr[char]]("/fd/2"))
    sys_execve_env(path, argv, envp)
    sys_exit(127)                                # unreached on success
    return 127


# --- p9_note() — write a note string, the SYS_KILL replacement ------

def p9_note(pid: int32, msg: Ptr[uint8]) -> int32:
    # /proc/<pid>/note — open for write, write the note string,
    # close. Plan 9's signal model: the message is what the target's
    # registered note handler sees. With no handler installed today
    # the kernel parks note_pending + the message on the target task;
    # the cross-task drain that consumes note_pending without a handler
    # is a separate kernel-side milestone (documented in
    # sys/src/9/port/sysnote.ad). Caller gets a clean return on the
    # write; semantics match what the F2 audit shipped for the rest of
    # the drift retirement family.
    path: Ptr[char] = _p9_build_note_path(pid)
    fd: int32 = sys_open_write(path)
    if fd < 0:
        return -1
    n: uint64 = _p9_strlen(msg)
    rc: int64 = sys_write(fd, msg, n)
    sys_close(fd)
    if rc < 0:
        return -1
    return 0


# --- p9_listdir() — read a directory, the SYS_LISTDIR replacement ---

def p9_listdir(path: Ptr[char], buf: Ptr[uint8], count: uint64) -> int64:
    # Open `path` as a directory and copy its rendered "NAME\n"
    # listing into `buf`. The dir fd's read backing is DEV_DIR_FILE
    # (_dirfile_read in sys/src/9/port/namec.ad) — it already produces
    # the exact same "NAME\n"-packed format the retired SYS_LISTDIR
    # used to return, so existing callers' parsing stays byte-identical
    # without any format conversion in this wrapper. Returns the bytes
    # written into `buf` (>= 0), or -1 on error (path doesn't exist,
    # isn't a directory, or read failed).
    fd: int32 = sys_open(path)
    if fd < 0:
        return -1
    total: int64 = 0
    # Loop reads until EOF or the caller's buffer is full. Most
    # directories fit in a single read of a 4 KiB+ buffer, but a tiny
    # buffer paired with a large directory must drain across multiple
    # reads — same shape sys_read uses on regular files.
    while cast[uint64](total) < count:
        rem: uint64 = count - cast[uint64](total)
        slice_ptr: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](
            cast[uint64](buf) + cast[uint64](total))
        n: int64 = sys_read(fd, slice_ptr, rem)
        if n < 0:
            sys_close(fd)
            return -1
        if n == 0:
            break                                 # EOF
        total = total + n
    sys_close(fd)
    return total


# --- F10-6: Plan 9 Dir record — first-class struct + wire format -----
#
# Adder has no `struct` keyword (see neighbouring modules' "Adder
# quirks" notes); a Dir VALUE is conveyed in userspace as a set of
# "current-record" module-scope fields populated by p9_dir_decode_at
# or by p9_diread. A caller invokes the decoder, then reads the
# DIR_CUR_* / DIR_NAME_BUF fields. This is the same parallel-array
# convention chan.ad / devfd.ad use for their "structs."
#
# QID type bits + DMDIR re-exported from lib/p9dir for convenience —
# userland callers can match against DIR_CUR_QTYPE without a second
# import.
#
# Decoder-side "current record" fields. After p9_dir_decode_at returns
# > 0, these hold the just-decoded record's values. The four string
# fields live in BSS scratch buffers (NUL-terminated for caller
# convenience; the wire format itself is NOT NUL-terminated).
DIR_NAME_MAX: uint64 = 256
DIR_UID_MAX:  uint64 = 64

DIR_CUR_QTYPE:   uint8  = 0
DIR_CUR_QVER:    uint32 = 0
DIR_CUR_QPATH:   uint64 = 0
DIR_CUR_MODE:    uint32 = 0
DIR_CUR_ATIME:   uint32 = 0
DIR_CUR_MTIME:   uint32 = 0
DIR_CUR_LENGTH:  uint64 = 0
DIR_CUR_NAME_LEN: uint64 = 0
DIR_CUR_UID_LEN:  uint64 = 0
DIR_CUR_GID_LEN:  uint64 = 0
DIR_CUR_MUID_LEN: uint64 = 0
DIR_CUR_NAME: Array[256, uint8]
DIR_CUR_UID:  Array[64, uint8]
DIR_CUR_GID:  Array[64, uint8]
DIR_CUR_MUID: Array[64, uint8]

def _p9_copy_str_capped(dst: Ptr[uint8], src: Ptr[uint8],
                        n: uint64, cap: uint64) -> uint64:
    # Copy min(n, cap-1) bytes from src to dst; NUL-terminate. Returns
    # the bytes copied (NOT counting the NUL). Used by the decoder to
    # land a wire-side length-prefixed string into a fixed BSS slot.
    take: uint64 = n
    if take + 1 > cap:
        take = cap - 1
    i: uint64 = 0
    while i < take:
        dst[i] = src[i]
        i = i + 1
    dst[take] = 0
    return take


def p9_dir_decode_at(buf: Ptr[uint8], off: uint64,
                     buf_len: uint64) -> uint64:
    # Decode ONE Dir record from buf+off. Populates the DIR_CUR_*
    # module-scope fields. Returns the record's reclen (>= P9_DIR_MIN_REC)
    # so the caller can advance `off += reclen` to the next record;
    # returns 0 on EOF (off >= buf_len) or a malformed record.
    if off >= buf_len:
        return 0
    if off + P9_DIR_FIXED_HDR > buf_len:
        return 0
    reclen: uint64 = cast[uint64](p9d_get_u16(buf, off))
    if reclen < P9_DIR_MIN_REC:
        return 0
    if off + reclen > buf_len:
        return 0
    DIR_CUR_QTYPE  = buf[off + 2]
    DIR_CUR_QVER   = p9d_get_u32(buf, off + 3)
    DIR_CUR_QPATH  = p9d_get_u64(buf, off + 7)
    DIR_CUR_MODE   = p9d_get_u32(buf, off + 15)
    DIR_CUR_ATIME  = p9d_get_u32(buf, off + 19)
    DIR_CUR_MTIME  = p9d_get_u32(buf, off + 23)
    DIR_CUR_LENGTH = p9d_get_u64(buf, off + 27)
    p: uint64 = off + P9_DIR_FIXED_HDR
    # name
    if p + 2 > off + reclen:
        return 0
    nl: uint64 = cast[uint64](p9d_get_u16(buf, p))
    p = p + 2
    if p + nl > off + reclen:
        return 0
    name_src: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](cast[uint64](buf) + p)
    DIR_CUR_NAME_LEN = _p9_copy_str_capped(
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](&DIR_CUR_NAME[0]), name_src, nl, DIR_NAME_MAX)
    p = p + nl
    # uid
    if p + 2 > off + reclen:
        return 0
    ul: uint64 = cast[uint64](p9d_get_u16(buf, p))
    p = p + 2
    if p + ul > off + reclen:
        return 0
    uid_src: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](cast[uint64](buf) + p)
    DIR_CUR_UID_LEN = _p9_copy_str_capped(
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](&DIR_CUR_UID[0]), uid_src, ul, DIR_UID_MAX)
    p = p + ul
    # gid
    if p + 2 > off + reclen:
        return 0
    gl: uint64 = cast[uint64](p9d_get_u16(buf, p))
    p = p + 2
    if p + gl > off + reclen:
        return 0
    gid_src: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](cast[uint64](buf) + p)
    DIR_CUR_GID_LEN = _p9_copy_str_capped(
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](&DIR_CUR_GID[0]), gid_src, gl, DIR_UID_MAX)
    p = p + gl
    # muid
    if p + 2 > off + reclen:
        return 0
    ml: uint64 = cast[uint64](p9d_get_u16(buf, p))
    p = p + 2
    if p + ml > off + reclen:
        return 0
    muid_src: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](cast[uint64](buf) + p)
    DIR_CUR_MUID_LEN = _p9_copy_str_capped(
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](&DIR_CUR_MUID[0]), muid_src, ml, DIR_UID_MAX)
    return reclen


# --- p9_listdir_records / p9_diread — Dir-record opt-in ---------------
#
# p9_listdir_records(path, buf, count) -> int64
#   Open `path` and ask the kernel to render the directory in Dir wire
#   format into `buf`. Returns bytes written (>= 0), or -1 on error
#   (path not a recognised Dir-mode-capable directory, or copy_to_user
#   failed). Internally invokes SYS_LISTDIR_RECORDS (318); the kernel
#   routes /srv to devsrv_list_dir, returns -ENOSYS for other paths
#   until those backings migrate.
#
# p9_diread(fd) is the Plan-9-idiomatic per-fd reader (one record per
# call). It cannot be implemented in pure userland on top of the legacy
# NAME\n directory fd shape — the kernel must know it is rendering Dir
# records. F10-6's minimal viable scope lands the syscall + the devsrv
# emitter; switching every directory fd's read backing to Dir records
# is the per-backing migration that follows. So `p9_diread` here is a
# THIN convenience: it pre-renders the entire directory via
# p9_listdir_records into a module-scope BSS buffer on the first call,
# then walks records out one at a time. The fd is tracked so a caller
# can iterate the same directory across calls; once that fd is closed
# the cursor resets.

extern def sys_listdir_records(path: Ptr[char], buf: Ptr[uint8],
                               count: uint64) -> int64
extern def sys_chan_dir_mode(fd: int32, mode: int32,
                             path: Ptr[char]) -> int32


def p9_chan_dir_mode(fd: int32, mode: int32, path: Ptr[char]) -> int32:
    # F10-6 followup userland wrapper: flip an already-open directory fd
    # into Dir-record mode. `path` is the absolute parent path the fd
    # was opened against (the kernel uses it to stat each entry during
    # the NAME\n -> Dir transform). Returns 0 on success, -1 on error.
    return sys_chan_dir_mode(fd, mode, path)


def p9_listdir_records(path: Ptr[char], buf: Ptr[uint8],
                       count: uint64) -> int64:
    # Userspace wrapper around SYS_LISTDIR_RECORDS (318). Returns bytes
    # written into `buf` (>= 0) or -errno on failure.
    return sys_listdir_records(path, buf, count)


# p9_diread cursor — module-scope BSS. The fd argument exists to give
# the v2 (per-fd Dir-mode) future the same call shape; v1 uses the fd
# only as a cache key — the actual data is re-fetched whenever the fd
# argument changes. A future migration that adds an OCREAD-Dir open
# flag will store the buffer cursor in the kernel chan instead.
P9_DIREAD_BUF_CAP: uint64 = 4096
_p9_diread_buf: Array[4096, uint8]
_p9_diread_path: Array[256, uint8]
_p9_diread_fd: int32 = -1
_p9_diread_total: uint64 = 0
_p9_diread_off: uint64 = 0


def p9_diread_open(path: Ptr[char]) -> int32:
    # v1 opener: pre-fills the Dir-record buffer for `path`. Returns a
    # synthetic fd-shape handle (>= 0) the caller passes to p9_diread.
    # The handle is just a small integer for cursor identification; it
    # is NOT a real kernel fd. Callers that already hold a kernel fd
    # for the dir can pass it to p9_diread directly; the v1 behaviour
    # ignores the actual fd value beyond using it as a cache key.
    n: int64 = p9_listdir_records(path,
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](&_p9_diread_buf[0]), P9_DIREAD_BUF_CAP)
    if n < 0:
        return -1
    # Cache the path so p9_diread can re-prime if the caller passes a
    # different fd in between (defensive — single-cursor v1).
    pp: Ptr[uint8] = cast[Ptr[uint8]](path)
    i: uint64 = 0
    while i < 255 and pp[i] != 0:
        _p9_diread_path[i] = pp[i]
        i = i + 1
    _p9_diread_path[i] = 0
    _p9_diread_fd    = 1                          # any non-(-1) value
    _p9_diread_total = cast[uint64](n)
    _p9_diread_off   = 0
    return _p9_diread_fd


def p9_diread(fd: int32) -> int32:
    # Read ONE Dir record into DIR_CUR_*. Returns 1 on hit, 0 on EOF,
    # -1 on error / no open dir. Caller must have called p9_diread_open
    # first. The fd argument is a forward-compatibility hook for the
    # per-fd-Dir-mode v2 migration; v1 ignores it beyond a sanity check
    # that an open is live.
    _unused: int32 = fd
    if _p9_diread_fd < 0:
        return -1
    if _p9_diread_off >= _p9_diread_total:
        return 0                                  # EOF
    rl: uint64 = p9_dir_decode_at(
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](&_p9_diread_buf[0]),
        _p9_diread_off, _p9_diread_total)
    if rl == 0:
        return -1                                 # malformed
    _p9_diread_off = _p9_diread_off + rl
    return 1


def p9_diread_close(fd: int32) -> int32:
    # Release the v1 cursor.
    _unused2: int32 = fd
    _p9_diread_fd    = -1
    _p9_diread_total = 0
    _p9_diread_off   = 0
    return 0
